GRCh38	FGFR1	TUMOR	p.N577K	NP_001167538.1:p.Asn577Lys	chr8	38417331		G	G	T	Missense_Mutation	SNP	38417331	FGFR1_N546K	G	T	.	PASS	GT:AF:DP	0/1:0.4:450	NM_001174067	T	missense_variant	MODERATE	FGFR1	2260	Transcript	NM_001174067.2	protein_coding	13/19		c.1731C>A	1933	1731	577	N/K	aaC/aaA	rs779707422&COSV58329537&COSV58330551		-1		SNV	EntrezGene	HGNC:3688								NP_001167538.1						RefSeq		G	G			deleterious_low_confidence(0)	probably_damaging(0.97)																																	pathogenic&likely_pathogenic	0&1&1	1&1&1	26619011&26822237&27626068&10766980&23819449&26942290&35488346						FAIL	-25	46	11	-25	0.00	0.00	0.00	0.02	FGFR1		2.7300e-01	224896				226759	Encephalocraniocutaneous_lipomatosis&Rosette-forming_glioneuronal_tumor		MONDO:MONDO:0013074&MedGen:C0406612&OMIM:613001&Orphanet:2396&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0025171&MONDO:MONDO:0016736&MedGen:C4331262&Orphanet:251975		NC_000008.11:g.38417331G>T	criteria_provided&_multiple_submitters&_no_conflicts	Pathogenic			SCV000292258&SCV001736964&SCV005902193	single_nucleotide_variant	SO:0001483	ClinGen:CA357830&OMIM:136350.0033&UniProtKB:P11362#VAR_075853		FGFR1:2260	SO:0001583&missense_variant	Neoplasm		Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0002664&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0003008&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0006741&MONDO:MONDO:0005070&MeSH:D009369&MedGen:C0027651		Oncogenic		criteria_provided&_single_submitter	SCV005094157		2	779707422	Dysembryoplastic_neuroepithelial_tumor&Diffuse_midline_glioma&_H3_K27M-mutant&Diffuse_pediatric-type_high-grade_glioma&_H3-wildtype_and_IDH-wildtype&Primary_intracranial_sarcoma&_DICER1-mutant&Embryonal_rhabdomyosarcoma&Rosette-forming_glioneuronal_tumor&Neuroblastoma		Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0033703&MONDO:MONDO:0005505&MedGen:C1266177&Orphanet:251946&MONDO:MONDO:0957196&MedGen:C4289688&MONDO:MONDO:0858939&MedGen:C5669918&MONDO:MONDO:0858967&MedGen:C5670660&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0006743&MONDO:MONDO:0009993&MedGen:C0206656&Orphanet:99757&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0025171&MONDO:MONDO:0016736&MedGen:C4331262&Orphanet:251975&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0003006&Human_Phenotype_Ontology:HP:0006738&MONDO:MONDO:0005072&MeSH:D009447&MedGen:C0027819&Orphanet:635		criteria_provided&_single_submitter	Tier_I_-_Strong		SCV007105526&SCV007105737&SCV007105741&SCV007105746&SCV007105753&SCV007105768	8:38417331-38417331	FGFR1	N546K	COSM19176	1	FGFR1	p.N577K								{'abstract': 'Rodon et al. Abstract# CT016. AACR 2023.', 'link': 'https://aacrjournals.org/cancerres/article/83/8_Supplement/CT016/725419'}	False	v7.0	.	.	The FGFR1 N577K mutation (also called N546K) is located in the kinase domain of the protein. This mutation has been identified in diffuse leptomeningeal tumors and papillary glioneuronal tumors (PMID: 27061725, 24777483). Expression of this mutation in vitro with rat and murine fibroblast cell lines and in vivo with a transgenic mouse model demonstrated that it is activating as measured by increased protein activity, proliferation, colony formation and transformed morphology compared to wildtype (PMID: 19224897, 23817572, 14602678). Additional in vitro studies with Ba/F3 cells expressing FGFR1 N546K demonstrate that the mutation is activating as measured by increased transformation compared to wildtype (PMID: 29533785). In vitro studies with Rat-1 cells expressing FGFR1 N577K also demonstrate that the mutation is activating as measured by increased kinase activity and transforming potential due to auto-phosphorylation compared to wildtype (PMID: 19224897). Preclinical studies with NIH3T3 cells expressing FGFR1 N577K demonstrated resistance to treatment with erdafitinib, AZD4547, infigratinib, futibatinib, pemigatinib and TKI258 as measured by sustained tumor growth and cellular proliferation following treatment (PMID: 34272467). In a Phase I trial, a patient with pilocytic astrocytoma harboring FGFR1 N577K was treated with pemigatinib and demonstrated partial response (PMID: 35176457). In a Phase II trial, three patients with breast cancer harboring FGFR1 N577K were treated with pemigatnib and demonstrated progressive disease (Abstract: Rodon et al. Abstract# CT016. AACR 2023. https://aacrjournals.org/cancerres/article/83/8_Supplement/CT016/725419).	.	LEVEL_Fda3	FGFR1, a receptor tyrosine kinase, is altered by mutation, chromosomal rearrangement or amplification in various cancer types including lung and breast cancers.	True	01/11/2023	.	.	24777483|19224897|29533785|23817572|34272467|35176457|14602678|27061725	.	.	N577K	2260	FGFR1	GRCh38	.	MUTATION	.	LEVEL_4	.	The FGFR1 N577K mutation is likely oncogenic.	False			LEVEL_Fda3					The FGFR1 N577K mutation (also called N546K) is located in the kinase domain of the protein. This mutation has been identified in diffuse leptomeningeal tumors and papillary glioneuronal tumors (PMID: 27061725, 24777483). Expression of this mutation in vitro with rat and murine fibroblast cell lines and in vivo with a transgenic mouse model demonstrated that it is activating as measured by increased protein activity, proliferation, colony formation and transformed morphology compared to wildtype (PMID: 19224897, 23817572, 14602678). Additional in vitro studies with Ba/F3 cells expressing FGFR1 N546K demonstrate that the mutation is activating as measured by increased transformation compared to wildtype (PMID: 29533785). In vitro studies with Rat-1 cells expressing FGFR1 N577K also demonstrate that the mutation is activating as measured by increased kinase activity and transforming potential due to auto-phosphorylation compared to wildtype (PMID: 19224897). Preclinical studies with NIH3T3 cells expressing FGFR1 N577K demonstrated resistance to treatment with erdafitinib, AZD4547, infigratinib, futibatinib, pemigatinib and TKI258 as measured by sustained tumor growth and cellular proliferation following treatment (PMID: 34272467). In a Phase I trial, a patient with pilocytic astrocytoma harboring FGFR1 N577K was treated with pemigatinib and demonstrated partial response (PMID: 35176457). In a Phase II trial, three patients with breast cancer harboring FGFR1 N577K were treated with pemigatnib and demonstrated progressive disease (Abstract: Rodon et al. Abstract# CT016. AACR 2023. https://aacrjournals.org/cancerres/article/83/8_Supplement/CT016/725419).	['24777483', '19224897', '29533785', '23817572', '34272467', '35176457', '14602678', '27061725']	[{'abstract': 'Rodon et al. Abstract# CT016. AACR 2023.', 'link': 'https://aacrjournals.org/cancerres/article/83/8_Supplement/CT016/725419'}]	['Oncogenic Mutations']	Erdafitinib		LEVEL_4	LEVEL_Fda3		['31088831', '32463741']		Fexagratinib and erdafitinib are orally available, small molecule FGFR1-4 tyrosine kinase inhibitors. There are promising laboratory and anecdotal clinical data to support use of fexagratinib and erdafitinib monotherapies in patients with FGFR1-mutated solid tumors. In the Phase II NCI-MATCH (EAY131) Subprotocol W (NCT02465060) trial of fexagratinib for 48 patients with FGFR-altered (n=20, FGFR1/2 amplification, n=19, FGFR2/3 single-nucleotide variants (SNV), n=9, FGFR1/3 fusions) refractory cancers, lymphomas or myelomas (33.3% breast, 12.5% urothelial, 10.4% cervical, 8.3% endometrial, 35.5% other rare malignancies), the median progression-free survival (PFS) was 3.4 months, the six-month PFS rate was 15% (90% CI=8-31) and the overall response rate (ORR) was 8% (90% CI=3-18), with four partial responses (PR) (n=1, FGFR2 Y376C, n=1, FGFR3 A393E, n=2, FGFR3-TACC3), in all evaluable patients (PMID: 32463741). Of patients with FGFR1-amplified (n=17) and FGFR1-rearranged (n=1) tumors in the Phase II NCI-MATCH (EAY131) Subprotocol W (NCT02465060) trial, eight patients demonstrated stable disease (SD) (n=7, FGFR1 amplification, n=1, FGFR1-BAG4) and six patients demonstrated progressive disease (PD) (n=6, FGFR1 amplification) (PMID: 32463741). __In the Phase I (NCT01703481) trial of erdafitinib in 187 patients with advanced solid tumors (19% breast, 16% urothelial, 13% non-small cell lung, 7% glioblastoma, 6% cholangiocarcinoma, ovarian, head and neck, 1% gastric, 26% other), the ORR was 11% (95% CI=7-17), with an 11% (n=21) PR rate, 16% (n=29) SD rate and 56% (n=104) PD rate in all evaluable patients (PMID: 31088831). Of patients with FGFR-mutated solid tumors (n=92 [n=11, cholangiocarcinoma, n=13, glioblastoma, n=27, urothelial, n=20, non-small cell lung, n=29, breast, n=8, ovarian, n=6, head and neck, n=1 gastric, n=20, other]), the ORR was 21% (95% CI=13-30), with a 21% (n=19) PR rate, 21% (n=19) SD rate and 50% (n=46) PD rate (PMID: 31088831).	5.0					All Solid Tumors	SOLID			-1.0	SOLID	['Oncogenic Mutations']	Fexagratinib		LEVEL_4	LEVEL_Fda3		['31088831', '32463741']		Fexagratinib and erdafitinib are orally available, small molecule FGFR1-4 tyrosine kinase inhibitors. There are promising laboratory and anecdotal clinical data to support use of fexagratinib and erdafitinib monotherapies in patients with FGFR1-mutated solid tumors. In the Phase II NCI-MATCH (EAY131) Subprotocol W (NCT02465060) trial of fexagratinib for 48 patients with FGFR-altered (n=20, FGFR1/2 amplification, n=19, FGFR2/3 single-nucleotide variants (SNV), n=9, FGFR1/3 fusions) refractory cancers, lymphomas or myelomas (33.3% breast, 12.5% urothelial, 10.4% cervical, 8.3% endometrial, 35.5% other rare malignancies), the median progression-free survival (PFS) was 3.4 months, the six-month PFS rate was 15% (90% CI=8-31) and the overall response rate (ORR) was 8% (90% CI=3-18), with four partial responses (PR) (n=1, FGFR2 Y376C, n=1, FGFR3 A393E, n=2, FGFR3-TACC3), in all evaluable patients (PMID: 32463741). Of patients with FGFR1-amplified (n=17) and FGFR1-rearranged (n=1) tumors in the Phase II NCI-MATCH (EAY131) Subprotocol W (NCT02465060) trial, eight patients demonstrated stable disease (SD) (n=7, FGFR1 amplification, n=1, FGFR1-BAG4) and six patients demonstrated progressive disease (PD) (n=6, FGFR1 amplification) (PMID: 32463741). __In the Phase I (NCT01703481) trial of erdafitinib in 187 patients with advanced solid tumors (19% breast, 16% urothelial, 13% non-small cell lung, 7% glioblastoma, 6% cholangiocarcinoma, ovarian, head and neck, 1% gastric, 26% other), the ORR was 11% (95% CI=7-17), with an 11% (n=21) PR rate, 16% (n=29) SD rate and 56% (n=104) PD rate in all evaluable patients (PMID: 31088831). Of patients with FGFR-mutated solid tumors (n=92 [n=11, cholangiocarcinoma, n=13, glioblastoma, n=27, urothelial, n=20, non-small cell lung, n=29, breast, n=8, ovarian, n=6, head and neck, n=1 gastric, n=20, other]), the ORR was 21% (95% CI=13-30), with a 21% (n=19) PR rate, 21% (n=19) SD rate and 50% (n=46) PD rate (PMID: 31088831).	5.0					All Solid Tumors	SOLID			-1.0	SOLID	True	True	True	Likely Gain-of-function	24777483;19224897;29533785;23817572;34272467;35176457;14602678;27061725;Rodon et al. Abstract# CT016. AACR 2023.(https://aacrjournals.org/cancerres/article/83/8_Supplement/CT016/725419)	Likely Oncogenic					Erdafitinib,Fexagratinib			LEVEL_4	LEVEL_4		31088831;32463741											450	0/1	T	missense_variant	FGFR1	2260	Gene	ENST00000341462.5	ENST00000341462.5:c.1638C>A	NP_075598.2:p.Asn546Lys	N546K	515	ASN546LYS/RS779707422	https://civicdb.org/links/variants/515	FGFR1_N546K	511			NM_023110.2:c.1638C>A/NP_075598.2:p.Asn546Lys/ENST00000341462.5:c.1638C>A/NC_000008.10:g.38274849G>T	CA357830	224896																				
